>Is it possible to determine the long/lat (and the size of the world/sun radius) on a flat plane using shadows cast by gnomons and known time differences?
It was done in historical times, so yes.
But they had access to a site within the tropics (so there has to be tropics*) so they could establish what day the sun was directly overhead, then take a measurement a large-but-known distance north, at noon.

The length of the shadow of the gnomon at noon at site B when the gnomon has no shadow at noon on site A can be used, along with the longitudinal distance between the sites, to calculate the circumference of the planet, assuming it's spherical. Once you know the circumference, you can calculate your latitude, given you have a magic bullshit time-difference-determining-machine.

In real history, a timekeeping device that was accurate enough to navigate by and could be transported whilst you were navigating without losing the time was not invented before 1770.

Anyways, the trick is to take your measurements at noon, because that reduces the problem from a 3d geometry problem to a 2d geometry problem. You can always tell it's noon, because that's when the shadow is shortest that day.

* if there's no tropics, this always works regardless, because every day is the same length. But your site A needs to be actually on the equator.

>ext4 handles small files faster than exfat
No it doesn't, it handles them basically the same:
ExFAT - file exists as a "directory entry" that's a tuple of "filename" and a pointer into a linked list of pointers into the disk (that can also be an extent; this is an improvement over FAT32)
Ext4 - file exists as an "inode", that's a short array of pointers into the disk; the last pointer goes to a block on the disk that's basically a larger inode. The inode can also use extents, this is an improvement over ext3.

In either case, allocating a small file means marking a block as used, and creating a directory entry that points to it. On ext3/ext4 you also need to write to an inode, this extra layer is necessary because ext supports hardlinks (FAT also supports hardlinks, but only as a form of filesystem corruption, not as an intended feature).

Are you maybe thinking of NTFS? For small files, NTFS can pack the data stream (which conceptually on NTFS is just another type of metadata, just like the filename) into the directory entry. So on NTFS, a directory with loads of small files in it looks kinda similar to a single medium-sized file.
